english:
  title: A Refutation of the Biography of Han Xin
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: "Upon reading the biography of Han Xin in the Records of Han, I find matters that demand refutation. I venture to present my argument thus:\n\nHan Xin's crime was indeed beyond forgiveness. Yet the High Ancestor cannot be said to bear no blame, and the historical brush of Ban Gu lacks impartiality.\n\nWhen a ruler harbors suspicion of his minister, it is proper that the minister bow his head and await execution. But if suspicion itself plants the seed of betrayal in the minister's heart, there is no greater crime for a subject than this. Such was Han Xin's transgression—unpardonable indeed. Yet Han Xin's crime was fundamentally cultivated by the High Ancestor himself. How so? When slanderers accused Han Xin of rebellion, the High Ancestor believed them and grew anxious—a failure of discernment. Among slanderous words, some remain ambiguous and unclear, while others may be judged at once. \n\nConsider Han Xin's position when Liu Bang and Xiang Yu contended for supremacy. With talent without equal in the land, with the gaze of eagle and tiger, in that moment the fate of all under heaven rested in his single hand—ally with Chu and Han would fall, ally with Han and Chu would perish. Yet Han Xin chose Han, achieved the unification of all lands, and became a minister. Moreover, Kuai Tong himself had urged Han Xin to divide the realm threefold, but Han Xin could not bear to betray Han and rejected the scheme. Given the circumstances of that time when such a path was possible, that he did not rebel shows his loyalty clearly. How much more so when all under heaven had become one family—would he truly seek to defy the great Han with merely the small region of Huaiyin? This can be judged at once.\n\nIf the High Ancestor truly lacked the discernment to judge fairly and feared Han Xin's rebellion, could he not have subdued a mere Huaiyin with the forces of ten thousand chariots? Why resort to the deception of a false excursion to Yunmeng to capture him there? Alas! That the master of all under heaven should employ false stratagem to deceive one subject—how could he then govern the myriad nations? When Han Xin was brought to Luoyang, he was pardoned because he bore no guilt. If the High Ancestor knew him innocent, he should have left him his kingdom and thereby eased his resentment. Instead, he demoted him to marquis, inflaming his grievance. This is like treading on a sleeping tiger's tail to wake it. Thus Han Xin grew to resent Han and feared his certain execution, compelling him against his will to plot rebellion. Was this not the High Ancestor's own doing? So I say: the High Ancestor cannot be absolved of fault.\n\nBan Gu wrote in his judgment: \"Han Xin seized temporary advantage through deception, achieved merit through cunning force, aroused suspicion of the powerful, and ultimately plotted treason, ending in destruction.\" As for his being \"suspected and plotting treason to his doom\"—this is true. But as for \"achieving merit through cunning force\"—I know not what he means. When Han Xin broke the mighty Chu, captured the King of Wei, seized Xia Shuo, and struck Lung Ju, he employed stratagems of cunning, yes—but this is brilliance of generalship, not deception. War values constant transformation; sometimes one employs stratagems. Without Han Xin's stratagems, neither would the High Ancestor have gained all under heaven. If we call this deception, then the High Ancestor, employing a minister of cunning force, could not be said to have won the realm righteously. True deception would be the High Ancestor's false excursion to Yunmeng or Xiao He's trick in delivering Han Xin to Empress Lü—yet Ban Gu does not censure these. Does he conceal them because they were acts of sage rulers and worthy ministers? As for \"seizing temporary advantage through stratagems,\" Xiao He, Cao Can, and Zhang Liang all did likewise. Why Han Xin alone? Therefore I say: the historical brush of Ban Gu lacks impartiality."
  footnotes:
    - 'Yunmeng: A hunting ground where the High Ancestor falsely claimed to be going when he actually captured Han Xin'
    - 'Kuai Tong: A strategist who urged Han Xin to divide the realm into three powers during the Chu-Han conflict'
    - 'Empress Lü: The wife of the High Ancestor, who later orchestrated Han Xin''s execution'
    - The five military campaigns mentioned—against Chu, Wei, Xia Shuo, and Lung Ju—were Han Xin's most celebrated victories
